03968nam a22004935i 9780822377504DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223775047 a10.1515/97808223775042doi  a(DE-B1597)551768  a(OCoLC)1172404946  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0250002bisacsh1 aStephen, Lynn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWe Are the Face of Oaxaca :bTestimony and Social Movements /cLynn Stephen. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b26 photographs, 1 table, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps, Illustrations, and Videoclips -- tAcronyms and Abbreviations -- tAbout the Website -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Testimony: Human Rights, and Social Movements -- t2 Histories and Movements: Antecedents to the Social Movement of 2006 -- t3 The Emergence of APPO and the 2006 Oaxaca Social Movement -- t4 Testimony and Human Rights Violations in Oaxaca -- t5 Community and Indigenous Radio in Oaxaca: Testimony and Participatory Democracy -- t6 The Women's Takeover of Media in Oaxaca: Gendered Rights "to Speak" and "to Be Heard" -- t7 The Economics and Politics of Conflict: Perspectives from Oaxacan Artisans, Merchants, and Business Owners -- t8 Indigenous Activism: The Triqui Autonomous Municipality, APPO Juxtlahuaca, and Transborder Organizing in APPO-L.A. -- t9 From Barricades to Autonomy and Art: Youth Organizing in Oaxaca -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA massive uprising against the Mexican state of Oaxaca began with the emergence of the Popular Assembly of the Peoples of Oaxaca (APPO) in June 2006. A coalition of more than 300 organizations, APPO disrupted the functions of Oaxaca's government for six months. It began to develop an inclusive and participatory political vision for the state. Testimonials were broadcast on radio and television stations appropriated by APPO, shared at public demonstrations, debated in homes and in the streets, and disseminated around the world via the Internet.The movement was met with violent repression. Participants were imprisoned, tortured, and even killed. Lynn Stephen emphasizes the crucial role of testimony in human rights work, indigenous cultural history, community and indigenous radio, and women's articulation of their rights to speak and be heard. She also explores transborder support for APPO, particularly among Oaxacan immigrants in Los Angeles. The book is supplemented by a website featuring video testimonials, pictures, documents, and a timeline of key events.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822377504zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822377504423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822377504.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles